<HEADLINE>
FT  03 NOV 93 / Venezuela lets foreign bankers in
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOSEPH MANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CARACAS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FOREIGN investors will be allowed a place in Venezuela's financial system in
the most sweeping legislation the country's banks have faced in 20 years.
President Ramon Velasquez yesterday signed a law reforming banking and
finance.
The reform, which takes effect from the start of next year, is the last big
element in an ambitious economic adjustment programme initiated in early
1989. Among the main provisions are: foreign financial institutions may hold
majority stakes in Venezuelan banks.
the Superintendency of Banks, the government supervisory agency for
financial institutions is given independence and new authority.
stiffer capital requirements for banks are established.
financial institutions are provided with a modern legal framework.
